[Heading 2] 5.1 Contact record
[Normal] The contact record is the person-level entity. It should store the person's raw imported name, normalized name, current edited name, email, LinkedIn URL, title, role, phone if available, location, source batch, consent status, email health status, and any custom fields that came with the original row. The contact should not be treated as a flat spreadsheet line. It should be a stateful object with history. That means the system must preserve the imported version of each important field, the normalized version created by the cleaning pipeline, and the current user-edited value when the user corrects the record.
[Normal] The contact also carries operational metadata. It must know whether it is ready, drafted, queued, sent, replied, bounced, invalid, risky, duplicate, suppressed, or archived. It must know when it was last checked, when it was last contacted, and whether it belongs to a suppression list. It must also know whether it is safe for AI to draft against it. That safety depends on both the contact's own data and the company context attached to it.
[Heading 2] 5.2 Company record
[Normal] The company record is the anchor of the system. It stores the organization's raw name, normalized name, domain, industry, size range, location, website, and any company-level research notes. It should also store the current internal summary of what the company appears to do, what problems the business can solve there, and which contacts are already connected to it. A company record exists even when only one contact is known. If a company name is missing during import, the system should create a placeholder rather than leaving the contact floating without context.
[Normal] The company object is where shared intelligence lives. A company can have one research card, one set of notes, one observed pain-point profile, and one set of relevant solution angles. All contacts at that company should reuse this context automatically. This is what keeps the outreach process efficient and consistent. It prevents the platform from re-researching the same account for every person and helps the user keep a single view of the company story.
[Heading 2] 5.3 Batch record
[Normal] Every import must create a batch record. The batch identifies the source file, the user who uploaded it, the time of import, the file hash, the mapping profile used, and the current processing status. The batch is the backbone of traceability. It should answer where the data came from, how it was interpreted, which rows were accepted, which rows were rejected, and whether the file has already been seen. If a later problem appears in the database, the batch record is what lets the team trace the issue back to its origin.
[Heading 2] 5.4 Capability asset
[Normal] Capability assets are the company's internal knowledge objects. They can represent a service line, a packaged solution, a case study, a proof point, a common objection response, or a pre-approved call-to-action. The platform should treat these assets as structured content rather than loose text documents. Each capability asset should carry a title, summary, category, service line, target industries, target roles, associated problems, supporting evidence, version, active status, and source document references. The AI drafting engine should not need to read the entire document when a smaller, structured capability summary is enough.
[Heading 2] 5.5 Research card
[Normal] The research card is the company-level context block. It stores approved observations about the company and its industry, such as what the business appears to sell, what size or footprint it has, what public signals are available, and what internal notes have already been captured. The card should separate facts from hypotheses. Facts are sourced or observed. Hypotheses are internal working ideas that help with outreach but are not presented as certainty. This distinction matters because the AI should be able to write a relevant message without turning speculation into false claims.
[Heading 2] 5.6 Draft, queue, reply, and audit entities
[Normal] The draft entity stores the AI-generated subject, body, CTA, and any explanation metadata used for internal review. The queue entity stores the sendable item, schedule, mailbox, and send status. The reply entity stores message threading information and classification. The bounce entity stores delivery failure details. The suppression entity stores reasons a lead should never be contacted again or should be paused for a time. The audit entity stores the full change history of the system. Together, these entities make the platform explainable and recoverable.
[Heading 1] 6. Ingestion and Batch Management
[Heading 2] 6.1 Standard upload template
[Normal] The platform should accept a standard Excel or CSV template, but it should not force the user to rebuild every source file by hand before import. The import interface should allow column mapping so that different source sheets can be aligned to the internal schema. The key requirement is consistency after ingestion, not rigidity before it. A file can contain many columns, but the system must know which ones are core fields, which are custom fields, and which are simply metadata that should be ignored.
[Normal] The template should support a small set of required identifiers and then allow additional company and contact columns as needed. Because the platform is internal, the template should reflect the company's actual operating data rather than an artificial vendor schema. If a user has email, LinkedIn, company name, website, title, address, or any other useful detail, the system should accept it as long as it can be mapped or stored cleanly. The goal is not to reduce the data into a narrow form; the goal is to make the data dependable after it enters the system.
[Heading 2] 6.2 Column mapping memory
[Normal] The first time a file type is imported, the user should map the columns to the internal schema. The system should save that mapping as an import profile. On later uploads with similar headers, the platform should auto-map the columns and only ask the user to confirm if something changed. This saves time and reduces mistakes. A team that imports from the same source repeatedly should not have to re-teach the system the same structure every week.
[Normal] Mapping memory should be keyed by the header row shape or by a named profile chosen by the user. If the source layout changes, the system should not silently guess. It should show the mismatch. This is especially important for fields that look similar but have different meanings, such as company title versus job title or company location versus contact location. Import convenience is useful only if it does not destroy data quality.
[Heading 2] 6.3 Staging and review
[Normal] Imports should land in staging first. Staging is the safe buffer between raw input and the master database. Every row should be classified in staging as clean, questionable, duplicate, or invalid. Clean rows can move forward automatically. Questionable rows should wait for human review. Invalid rows should stay visible with a clear reason. Duplicates should be held long enough for the system or the reviewer to decide whether to merge, reject, or keep one version.
[Normal] This stage makes the system resilient. If a file is messy, the user does not have to throw the whole import away. If one row has a malformed email but the rest of the batch is good, the clean records can still progress. If a company name is slightly different but clearly the same organization, the platform can surface the conflict instead of guessing in silence.
[Heading 2] 6.4 Batch traceability and archive
[Normal] Every row in the master database must retain a pointer to the batch that created it. This creates a chain of custody from source file to final record. The batch itself should be archivable so that old imports can be hidden from the active list without being deleted. Archiving should be reversible because old source data can become important later when the team needs to explain where a record came from or reprocess a file after the schema changes.
[Normal] The system should also allow error export. When a row fails validation or needs review, the user should be able to download a file containing the problem rows and the reason for each issue. This makes remediation practical. A large internal list is not useful if the operator cannot quickly fix a few bad rows and re-import them.
[Heading 2] 6.5 File hash protection
[Normal] The platform should hash incoming files and reject exact re-imports of the same file. This prevents duplicate batches, accidental double counting, and repeated processing of the same source. The hash should be stored with the batch so that the system can answer whether a file has been seen before. If a file is intentionally reprocessed, the operator should have to make that choice visibly rather than causing a duplicate by mistake.
[Heading 1] 7. Data Quality and Validation
[Heading 2] 7.1 Normalization pipeline
[Normal] The cleaning pipeline should turn inconsistent spreadsheet entries into stable machine-readable values. Names should be trimmed and normalized for spacing and casing. Company names should be preserved in their raw human-readable form, but a separate normalized match key should be created for duplicate detection. Websites should be standardized so that protocol noise and trailing slashes do not break matching. LinkedIn URLs should be converted into a predictable form. Phone numbers should be formatted consistently when possible. Location fields should be normalized enough to support searching and grouping without pretending that every source sheet used the same naming convention.
[Normal] The point of normalization is not to make the data look pretty. The point is to make downstream logic reliable. Duplicate detection, scoring, search, and research all depend on the data being comparable. A user should be able to search for a company once and find it again later, even if the imported source changed the capitalization or punctuation.
[Heading 2] 7.2 Email health score
[Normal] The platform should treat email validity as a confidence score rather than as a magical truth. A record may be syntactically valid, domain-resolvable, and still not be safely contactable. A record may be unknown because the system has not yet sent to it or seen enough feedback. A record may be risky because the domain looks valid but bounce history or poor structure suggests caution. A record may be invalid because the address is malformed, clearly disposable, or repeatedly rejected.
[Normal] This distinction is important because internal systems often confuse "usable for drafting" with "safe to send." The platform should keep those ideas separate. A risky or unknown record can still be stored, researched, segmented, and drafted against. It just should not be released into the send queue until it has the right status. The score should be recalculated on a schedule and also on demand when new signal arrives.
[Heading 2] 7.3 Weekly refresh
[Normal] The system should run a weekly health job across non-suppressed contacts. That job should refresh syntax checks, domain checks, MX checks, disposable-domain checks, bounce history, and reply history. The goal is not to prove the existence of an inbox with perfect certainty. The goal is to keep the database fresh enough that the send queue does not fill with stale addresses. If a contact becomes bad or starts bouncing, the system should move it out of the active set quickly.
[Normal] Weekly refresh is also a data trust mechanism. It shows the team that the platform is not a dead archive. It is an active list that learns from use. Every bounce, reply, and pause contributes to the score and to the health of the database. That feedback loop is one of the most valuable parts of the system because it keeps the lead base useful over time.
[Heading 2] 7.4 Manual review queue
[Normal] Some records should be routed to a manual review queue when the system is uncertain. This queue may include risky email records, ambiguous company matches, incomplete rows, or contacts whose duplicate confidence is too low for automatic resolution. The reviewer can accept, reject, or edit the row. The manual queue keeps the system honest. It is better to admit uncertainty than to hide it under an automated decision.
[Normal] The review queue should be efficient. It should show the raw value, the normalized value, the source batch, the reason for the flag, and the most relevant company context. A reviewer should be able to resolve a row without opening five different screens. The queue is not a punishment; it is the place where the platform protects its own quality.
[Heading 1] 8. Duplicate Detection and Merge Governance
[Heading 2] 8.1 Contact identity rules
[Normal] Contact duplicates should be identified using a clear priority order. The strongest match is exact email. If email is not available or is intentionally absent for a non-send-ready record, exact LinkedIn URL is the next strongest match. If those are absent or inconclusive, the system can compare normalized full name plus normalized company name. Fuzzy matching can help catch small inconsistencies, but it should never be allowed to override strong evidence without review.
[Normal] The point of the identity rules is to reduce accidental duplication without collapsing distinct people into one record. In a large dataset, two people can share a name and even work at the same company. The deduplication engine must therefore be careful. Exact identifiers should drive automation. Ambiguous matches should drive review. The system should prefer a cautious false negative over an incorrect merge when the evidence is weak.
[Heading 2] 8.2 Company identity rules
[Normal] Company duplicates should be matched using exact website domain first, then normalized company name. Company matching is often easier than contact matching, but it still needs guardrails. Businesses may have multiple domains, legal entity names, or brand names. The system should not destroy that complexity. It should simply create one company anchor with enough metadata to recognize that multiple source variants may refer to the same organization.
[Normal] If the company cannot be confidently identified, the platform should create a placeholder record and allow later correction. The important thing is that the contact is never left without a company link. Even a placeholder is better than a floating row because it preserves the relational structure and gives the reviewer a place to fix the record later.
